<p><b>UNITED 
NATIONS 
</b></p>
<p> <b>A 
</b> 
</p>
<p><b>General Assembly</b> Distr. 
LIMITED 
</p>
<p>A/HRC/S-8/L.2 
27 November 2008 
</p>
<p>Original:  ENGLISH 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Eighth special session 
28 November 2008 
</p>
<p><b>Egypt (on behalf of the African Group):  draft resolution 
S-8/... Situation of Human Rights in the East of the  
</b></p>
<p><b>Democratic Republic of the Congo 
</b></p>
<p> <i>The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling</i> General Assembly resolutions 60/251 and 61/296, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling</i> <i>also </i>Human Rights Council resolutions 5/1, 5/2, and 7/20, 
</p>
<p> <i>Reiterating</i> the principles and objectives of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and 
the International Covenants on Human Rights, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling also </i>the decision of the 10th African Union Assembly on Peace and Security 
situation in Africa, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling further </i>the provisions of the Pact on Security, Stability and Development in the 
Great Lakes Region, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling further</i> African efforts to address the situation in the Democratic Republic of 
the Congo, including: </p>

<p>A/HRC/S-8/L.2 
page 2 
 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) Actes d&#8217;engagement signed by the parties to the peace process in the region of Kivu 
within the framework of the Conference on Peace, Security and Development in the provinces of 
North and South Kivu, held in Goma from 6 to 23 January 2008, 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) Great Lakes Region Summit of 7 November 2008 on the situation in the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo, 
</p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) Extra-Ordinary Summit of the SADC Heads of State and Government held on 
9 November 2008, 
</p>
<p> (<i>d</i>) Summit of heads of State members of the Commission of the Gulf of Guinea, held on 
25 November 2008, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Reiterates its serious concern</i> at the deteriorating human rights and humanitarian 
situation in North Kivu, since the resumption of hostilities on 28 August 2008 and calls upon all 
concerned parties to scrupulously respect the provisions of International Human Rights Law and 
International Humanitarian Law, to, ensure the protection of the civilian population and to 
facilitate the work of humanitarian agencies; 
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Expresses concern</i> at the deteriorating situation of refugees and internally displaced 
persons due to the escalation of the conflict in Kivu; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Reiterates further</i> the necessity to establish humanitarian corridors throughout the 
area so as to allow access and free movement of people and goods as well as to enable 
humanitarian agencies to provide the badly needed food, water, medication and shelter; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Condemns</i> the acts of violence, lack of cooperation and human rights violations 
committed in Kivu; 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Expresses support</i> to the efforts in the United Nations Secretary-General&#8217;s Special 
Envoy for the conflict in the east of the Democratic Republic of the Congo former president 
Olusegun Obasanjo, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community and the 
Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo in the search for a political solution to 
restore long-term peace and stability to the region, in particular within the Goma process and the 
Nairobi process; </p>

<p> A/HRC/S-8/L.2 
 page 3 
 
</p>
<p> 6. <i>Calls upon</i> the United Nations to strengthen the mandate of its Mission in the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo (MONUC) pertaining to the protection of civilians and to 
restore peace, security and stability in the region of Kivu of the Democratic Republic of 
the Congo, and calls upon all States to immediately provide assistance to the Mission in the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo, including through contributing personnel, to increase its 
ability to address the dire security and humanitarian situation in the region; 
</p>
<p> 7. <i>Calls upon</i> the international community to: 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) Seriously address the root causes of the conflict, including illicit exploitation of 
natural resources and the establishment of militia that are the basis of human rights violations 
and the humanitarian crisis in the region; 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) Continue to contribute to the promotion of peace and stability in the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo, and to assist the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo 
in the rehabilitation and economic construction of the country; 
</p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) Provide the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo with the various 
forms of assistance it requests, with the view to improving the humanitarian and human rights 
situation; 
</p>
<p> (<i>d</i>) Welcomes the cooperation of the Democratic Republic of the Congo with the 
thematic special procedures of the Council as well as the invitation it has extended to some 
individual special procedures and encourages the Government of the Democratic Republic of 
the Congo to strengthen its cooperation in this regard. 
</p>
<p>----- </p>

